ngland","England":"England","Redenhall, Norfolk, England":"Redenhall, Norfolk, England"},"nl":{"about 1423–about 1470":"circa 1423–circa 1470","1420–1470":"1420–1470","1450–1500":"1450–1500","1423–1470":"1423–1470","about 1470":"circa 1470","1423":"1423","1500":"1500","1455":"1455","1420":"1420","about 1423":"circa 1423","1450":"1450","1470":"1470","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, England","England":"England","Redenhall, Norfolk, England":"Redenhall, Norfolk, England"},"en":{"about 1423–about 1470":"about 1423–about 1470","1420–1470":"1420–1470","1450–1500":"1450–1500","1423–1470":"1423–1470","about 1470":"about 1470","1423":"1423","1500":"1500","1455":"1455","1420":"1420","about 1423":"about 1423","1450":"1450","1470":"1470","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, England","England":"England","Redenhall, Norfolk, England":"Redenhall, Norfolk, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Thomas","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English, French, Walloon, Breton, German, Dutch, Flemish, Danish, Greek, West Indian (mainly Haiti and Jamaica), and African (mainly Tanzania and Nigeria): from the personal name <i>Thomas</i>, of Biblical (New Testament) origin, from Aramaic <i>t’ōm’a</i>, a byname meaning ‘twin’. It was borne by one of the disciples of Christ, known for his scepticism about Christ's resurrection (John 20:24–29). The <i>Th-</i> spelling is organic, the initial letter of the name in the Greek New Testament being a theta. The English pronunciation as <i>t</i> rather than <i>th-</i> is the result of French influence from an early date. In Britain, the surname is widely distributed throughout the country, but especially common in Wales and Cornwall. In North America, the English form of the surname has absorbed many cognates from other languages (e.g. Assyrian/Chaldean or Arabic   Toma   and   Tuma  , Albanian   Toma   and   Thoma  , and Slavic surnames listed in 3 below), and their patronymics and other derivatives (e.g. Polish   Tomaszewski   and Slovenian <b>Tomažič</b>; see   Tomazic  ). In France, this surname is most common in the Vosges and Brittany. The name <i>Thomas</i> is also found among Christians in southern India (compare   Machan  ,   Mammen  , and   Oommen  ), but since South Indians traditionally do not have hereditary surnames, the southern Indian name was in most cases registered as such only after immigration of its bearers to the US. This surname is also very common among African Americans.","Native American (e.g. Navajo): adoption of the English personal name <i>Thomas</i> (see 1 above) as a surname.","Germanized or Americanized form of Polish   Tomas  , <b>Tomasz</b>, and <b>Tomaś</b>, Sorbian <b>Tomaš</b> (see also 4 below), Croatian <b>Tomaš</b> and   Tomas  , Slovenian <b>Tomaš</b> and <b>Tomaž</b>, Czech and Slovak <b>Tomáš</b>, all meaning ‘Thomas’."],"variants":[{"name":"Maas","meanings":["Dutch, Flemish, and North German: from a short form of the personal name   Thomas  ."]},{"name":"Mashak","meanings":["Americanized form of Polish <b>Maszak</b>: patronymic from a short form of the personal name <i>Tomasz</i> (see   Thomas  ) or possibly of a personal name beginning with <i>Ma-</i>. The surname <i>Maszak</i> is very rare in Poland.","In some cases also an Americanized form of Czech <b>Mašek</b> (see   Masek  ). Compare   Mashek  ."]},{"name":"Maschke","meanings":["German: from a Slavic-influenced (see below) pet form of the personal names   Thomas   (compare   Maas  ) or   Matthias  .","Germanized form of Sorbian <b>Mašk</b>, <b>Maška</b>, and <b>Maško</b>: from a pet form of the personal name <i>Domaš</i> or <i>Tomaš</i> (see   Thomas   3, 4), or of any name beginning with <i>Ma-</i>.","Germanized form of Czech <b>Mašek</b> (see   Masek  ) and Polish <b>Maszek</b>, both cognates of 2 above."]},{"name":"Toma","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Arabic/Muslim Kamal, Nabil, Salem, Kamil, Safa, Samir, Adil, Adnan, Aziz, Bahjat, Basem, Bashar.  Japanese Hiroshi, Takeo, Hideo, Isako, Izumi, Junichi, Kenji, Kiyoko, Masakazu, Rikuo, Sachi, Shigeo.","Romanian and Croatian: from the personal name <i>Toma</i>, an equivalent of   Thomas  . Compare   Tomas  .","Italian, French, Polish, Slovak, and Hungarian: from a short, pet, or dialect form of a personal name equivalent to   Thomas   (Italian <i>Tommaso</i>, French <i>Thomas</i>, Polish <i>Tomasz</i>, Slovak <i>Tomáš</i>, Hungarian <i>Tamás</i>)."]},{"name":"Mask","meanings":["English: unexplained.","German: from a pet form of the personal name   Thomas  ."]},{"name":"Masino","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Angelo, Ciro, Larraine.","Italian: from a short form of <b>Tommasino</b>, a pet form of thepersonal name <i>Tommaso</i> (see   Thomas  )."]},{"name":"Mascio","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Antonio, Carlo, Gino, Luigi, Paolo, Salvatore.","Italian:","(southern): from a variant of <i>Maso</i>, a short form of the personal name <i>Tommaso</i> (see   Thomas  ). Alternatively, perhaps from an Italianized form of the Albanian equivalent <i>Mashi</i>."]},{"name":"Masel","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt.","German: from a pet form of   Thomas  ."]},{"name":"Masi","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Angelo, Carmine, Mario, Vito, Carlo, Antonio, Alfonso, Armando, Filomena, Gerardo, Giovanni, Salvatore, Alfonse, Alfonsina, Amato, Anello, Canio, Emilio.","Italian: patronymic or plural form of <i>Maso</i>, a short form of the personal name <i>Tommaso</i> (see   Thomas  )."]},{"name":"Masiello","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Carlo, Rocco, Angelo, Carmine, Franco, Salvatore, Antonio, Carmino, Domenic, Domenica, Francesco, Mauro.","Italian (mainly Naples): from a pet form of the personal name <i>Tommaso</i> (see   Thomas  )."]}]},{"name":"Mary","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Latin <i>Maria</i> via Old Welsh <i>Meir</i>.  See  <b>Mary</b> ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":32,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"Mary Thomas was born about 1423, in Norfolk, England. She had at least 1 son with Samuel Walles. She died about 1470, in her hometown, at the age of 49."},"et":{"about 1423–about 1470":"umbes 1423–umbes 1470","1420–1470":"1420–1470","1450–1500":"1450–1500","1423–1470":"1423–1470","about 1470":"umbes 1470","1423":"1423","1500":"1500","1455":"1455","1420":"1420","about 1423":"umbes 1423","1450":"1450","1470":"1470","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, England","England":"England","Redenhall, Norfolk, England":"Redenhall, Norfolk, England"},"fi":{"about 1423–about 1470":"noin 1423–noin 1470","1420–1470":"1420–1470","1450–1500":"1450–1500","1423–1470":"1423–1470","about 1470":"noin 1470","1423":"1423","1500":"1500","1455":"1455","1420":"1420","about 1423":"noin 1423","1450":"1450","1470":"1470","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, England","England":"England","Redenhall, Norfolk, England":"Redenhall, Norfolk, England"},"fr":{"about 1423–about 1470":"environ 1423–environ 1470","1420–1470":"1420–1470","1450–1500":"1450–1500","1423–1470":"1423–1470","about 1470":"environ 1470","1423":"1423","1500":"1500","1455":"1455","1420":"1420","about 1423":"environ 1423","1450":"1450","1470":"1470","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, Angleterre","England":"Angleterre","Redenhall, Norfolk, England":"Redenhall, Norfolk, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Mary Thomas est née environ